<HL>
   Heredity Plays Major Role in Amount
   Of Fat a Person Gains, New Study Says
   ----
   By Jerry E. Bishop
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7C
</SO>
<IN>
MEDICAL AND BIOTECHNOLOGY (MTC)
</IN>
<LP>
   Inheritance plays a major role in how much fat a person
accumulates and where it builds up on the body, a new study
of twins found.
   An experiment in Canada, in which identical twins ate a
high-calorie diet for more than three months, found that
weight gain and fat distribution in one twin was remarkably
similar to that of his fellow twin but markedly different
from that of other, unrelated individuals. As identical twins
have identical genes, this indicated that the genes each pair
of twins shared played an important role in determining their
weight gain and fat distribution.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The study added new evidence that a predisposition to
being overweight or obese can be inherited. But scientists
cautioned against misinterpreting the new findings.
   "There is a risk" that publishing the results of the
studies "may lead the popular media to declare that what goes
on in the home really makes no difference" in whether a child
becomes an obese adult, warned an editorial published in this
week's New England Journal of Medicine where the two reports
were published.
   The studies don't mean that genes automatically dictate
that a person will be overweight or obese regardless of how
much or how little he or she eats. Instead, the genes
inherited from the parents merely influence the way the body
handles excess calories. In other words, a person could
inherit a predisposition to obesity but whether he actually
becomes obese could be influenced by eating habits.
   The Canadian experiment, carried out at Laval University
in Ste. Foy, Quebec, involved 12 pairs of male identical
twins who agreed to spend 100 days living with researchers in
a special dormitory. After they determined each man's
base-line daily calorie needs, the researchers made sure each
man ate an extra 1,000 calories a day six days a week. Thus,
over the 100 days each volunteer ate 84,000 more calories
than he needed.
   Weight gains varied widely among the 24 men, ranging from
five to 30 pounds per person over the 100 days. The aim of
the study was to find out how much of this difference among
individuals was due to hereditary factors and how much was
due to environmental factors, the excess calories in this
case.
   The researchers found that when comparing one twin with
his fellow twin, there was far less variation in weight gain
than seen in the group as a whole. This indicated that the
genes were having a major influence on how much of the extra
84,000 calories each person stored as fat.
   The researchers also found that increases in lean and fat
tissues in one twin was similar to that of his fellow twin
although such changes in the fat to lean ratio varied widely
among twin pairs. The same phenomenon was seen when the
distribution of newly gained fat was measured. If one twin
tended to gain fat in the abdominal skin, so did his twin.
Such correlation wasn't seen when comparing twin pairs.
   A second study at Pennsylvania State University of 93
pairs of identical twins separated early in life and reared
in different homes found that genetic factors were about
twice as important as the childhood home environment in
determining adult weight.
   The analysis, also published in the New England Journal,
found that each twin's body mass was more similar to his or
her identical but separated twin's body mass than it was to
other members of each twin's adoptive family.
   The researchers in the Pennsylvania State University study
estimated that genetic factors accounted for 70% of the
difference in body mass among individuals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900525-0154
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900525-0154.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Perkins Foods PLC Is Buying Up Firms
   In Effort to Develop European Network
   ----
   By Andrew Atkinson
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9A
</SO>
<CO>
   U.PKN
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Perkins Foods PLC, a small but hungry British
concern, is buying up bits of northern Europe's fragmented
foods industry in hopes of building a coherent manufacturing
and marketing network.
   Chairman Howard Phillips says his company, which deals in
a number of items from fresh produce to frozen pizzas,
intends to buy as many as six closely held companies across
the region this year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Our main area of development will be in added value
products," Mr. Phillips says, with the aim of capturing more
of the profit built into food goods at various stages on
their way to consumers.
   Earnings at Perkins have grown quickly in the two years
since Phillips and a new management team arrive. In 1989,
Perkins pretax profit more than tripled to 9.78 million
pounds ($16.5 million) from 2.84 million pounds in the
previous 15 months. Fully diluted per-share earnings stood at
7.8 pence, up 32% from 5.9 pence.
   Analysts expect pretax profit this year to rise 62% to
15.9 million pounds, with per-share earnings rising 17% to
9.15 pence. In 1991, they forecast a further 16% rise in
pretax profit to 18.5 million pounds and a 15% rise in
per-share earnings to 10.5 pence.
   With debt of just $1.6 million, gearing at 10% and a
strong cash flow, the company is in a strong position to make
still more acquisitions, says analyst Charlie Mills of London
stock brokers James Capel &amp; Co. Ltd.
   The type of foods company Phillips says he is looking for
is of medium size, already profitable with pretax earnings of
about 5 million pounds and with plenty of room for growth. He
isn't keen on buying large companies which might be past the
bloom of youth, or small ones which need extensive work to
get through start-up problems. Wherever possible, he wants
management to stay on.
   In 1987, an investment team led by Phillips and Michael
Davies, who with Phillips was once a director of Hanson PLC's
Imperial Foods Ltd., took an initial 12% stake in what was
then a largely family owned business, John Perkins Meats PLC.
   Phillips' management team quickly turned the company
upside-down. Perkins divested itself of the original meat
trading business and snapped up 12 companies for a total of
70 million pounds.
   In the process, Perkins has acquired a clutch of added
value units that include frozen food distributor Nuka, frozen
foodmaker Van der Made and mushroom canner Holland
Champignons.
   Peppinos, the West German pizza maker, remains among the
company's flagships. Costing an initial 34 million Deutsche
marks ($20.4 million), the frozen pizza maker gives Perkins
the first of other much-hoped-for acquisitions in West
Germany as prospects for a unified German market for food
grows ever-brighter. "We'd like very much to realize what's
happening there," he said.
   Phillips believes the Perkins strategy leave little to
recession, with business exposure spread among northern
Europe's healthiest economies.
   "We believe in spreading the risk and not exposing
ourselves too much in any one country," the chairman says.
While the British economy may be slowing, he adds, "I see
little evidence of a recession on the continent."
   Central to Perkins' vertical integration plans, says
Phillips, is the expansion of the company's frozen products
which include pizzas, potato snacks and seafood.
   Already, frozen-food manufacturing bases in Britain,
Germany and the Netherlands have boast sales outlets in
domestic markets and markets in Scandinavia, France, Belgium
and Italy thanks to a network of marketing and distributing
units including Perkins' Nuka and Sunbird subsidiaries.
   In its bid to extend the company still further, Perkins is
now considering Denmark, Sweden, Austria and Switzerland as
host countries to further acquisitions in a bid to extend the
company well into the 1990s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900525-0153
