<HL>
   Technology:
   Dell Computer Net
   More Than Doubled
   In Fiscal 1st Period
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   DELL
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   AUSTIN, Texas -- Boosted by unusually strong overseas
sales growth, Dell Computer Corp. said it had record revenue
and net income in its May 4 first quarter.
   Net income more than doubled to $5.3 million, or 28 cents
a share, from the year-earlier level of $2.1 million, or 11
cents a share. Revenue increased 38%, to $120.3 million from
$87.5 million a year earlier, reflecting the highest
quarterly sales in the computer maker's history.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Dell's earnings "exceeded our expectations," said Michael
Dell, chairman and chief executive. They also marked a sharp
turnaround from the past several quarters, when the company
was working off a surplus of high-cost inventory that
severely pinched its margins and reduced earnings to as low
as one cent a share.
   While domestic revenue was up 15% from a year ago, most of
Dell's gains were made overseas, where sales more than
doubled from last year's first quarter. International sales
now represent 36% of Dell's world-wide revenue, said Mr.
Dell, compared with 23% a year ago. Dell has international
subsidiaries in the United Kingdom, Canada, West Germany,
France and Sweden.
   But Mr. Dell cautioned that the current quarter will not
show the same growth rate, partly because much of the
first-quarter international sales gain was caused by year-end
government orders.
   And while Dell's domestic business is "holding its own,"
Mr. Dell added, margin pressures are increasing as
competitors try to increase market share through
more-aggressive pricing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
