<HL>
   U.K. Economic
   Data Show Rise
   In Output, Pay
   ----
   By Paulette Roberge
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- New U.K. economic data showed a continued rise
in industrial production against a background of steady wage
increases in manufacturing, reinforcing economists' views
that the Thatcher government is having mixed success in
cooling the economy.
   The Central Statistical Office reported industrial
production rose 1.8% in March from month-earlier levels,
while rising 1.7% from March 1989. In addition, unit wage
costs in the manufacturing sector, while easing 0.3% in March
from February, were up 7.5% from the year-earlier month.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The data come on top of a wider-than-expected April
merchandise trade deficit of 1.78 billion pounds ($3.01
billion), reported Wednesday.
   "One month ago, we had tentative signs" of a slowdown in
economic activity that could lead to lower inflation, says
David Owen, economist at Kleinwort Benson Securities. Now, he
says, that optimism appears to have been misplaced.
   A Treasury official noted that the year-on-year rise in
industrial production showed that the "rate of growth has
clearly slowed over the past year," as expected in the
current fiscal climate.
   But the market was anticipating a rise in industrial
production of only about 0.45%. The higher-than-expected rise
led many economists to revise next week's first-quarter
output-based Gross Domestic Product (GDP) figures upward to
stand even with quarter-earlier levels or to show a modest
gain.
   GDP in the fourth quarter was up 2% -- from a year
earlier. Chancellor of the Exchequer John Major has forecast
that GDP growth would be 1% for 1990.
   Although unit wage costs in the manufacturing sector
showed a modest fall in March, UBS-Phillips &amp; Drew Ltd.
economist Joe Roseman notes that wage settlements are still
running at an "uncomfortably high level" on an annualized
basis, putting considerable pressure on profit margins.
   The squeeze on profits has led to some employment
contraction in the manufacturing sector, which economists say
may shortly lead to lower wage demands. But they add that
this has yet to be felt in the service sector, where the wage
problem is exacerbated by an acute shortage of skilled labor.
   Mr. Roseman and other economists take comfort from the
historical pattern of high wage settlements of the early
1980s and early 1986, which were followed by sharp falls in
pay settlements. But these also suggest that any sudden
shakeouts in the labor market can't be expected in 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900525-0138
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900525-0138.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Thorn May Sell
   Light-Bulb Line
   To GTE Corp.
   ----
   By Richard L. Hudson and John J. Keller
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9A
</SO>
<CO>
   U.THN GTE
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
HOUSEHOLD AND PERSONAL-CARE PRODUCTS (HHP)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- In a sudden change of corporate strategy,
Britain's Thorn EMI PLC said it is discussing selling its big
European light bulb and light fixture business to GTE Corp.
of the U.S.
   Such a transaction, valued by London analysts at roughly
350 million pounds ($592.7 million), would expand Stamford,
Conn.-based GTE's European lighting business and strengthen
its standing in the increasingly fierce world lighting
market. The Thorn business is the world's fifth biggest
light-bulb maker, and claims to tie N.V. Philips of the
Netherlands as the largest manufacture of fixtures. GTE ranks
third in making light bulbs, but is a smaller player in
fixtures.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For Thorn, the move to sell what the company had
previously called a "core" business puzzled many London
financial analysts. Since 1985, when plunging profits and a
boardroom coup brought Chairman Colin Southgate to power, the
company has been in a near-constant state of reorganization.
It has shed a movie-making division and a semiconductor unit,
and has been trying to sell its defense-electronics division.
If lighting goes -- Thorn's original business at its 1928
founding -- two main divisions will remain: renting household
appliances, and publishing and recording music.
   A Thorn spokeswoman said the lighting-business talks were
necessitated by harsher market conditions. In the past few
years the world lighting industry has been consolidating,
with bigger companies buying smaller ones or forming
alliances. The Thorn business "wasn't of a sufficient size to
compete on an independent basis," she said. Also, according
to London-based analyst Ron Littleboy of Nomura Research
Institute, the Thorn lighting business's operating profit
slipped to about 36 million pounds in the year ended March
31, from 40 million pounds a year earlier. A Thorn spokesman
declined to comment on Mr. Littleboy's estimate.
   Neither Thorn nor GTE was willing to discuss the possible
sales terms. "Where'd they get that number?" responded Dean
Langford, president of GTE's Electrical Products Group, when
asked about London analysts' estimates of a possible 350
million-pound price tag. "It's a bit premature to say what
the price is going to be when we're just beginning
negotiations," he added.
   GTE and Thorn have already been partners for some time.
The two companies have a joint Italian light-bulb venture.
Mr. Langford said that combining with Thorn's business would
make GTE a "strong number two" in the world-wide lighting
business after Philips -- though it wasn't possible to
confirm that assessment independently. Mr. Langford said the
transaction would strengthen GTE in Italy, Belgium, the
Netherlands, Scandinavia and Australia.
</TEXT>
