<HL>
   Technology:
   Europe Defeats
   Japan's Proposal
   On TV Standard
   ---
   Move Indicates Each Side
   Will Separately Develop
   High-Definition Sets
   ----
   By Bob Davis
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
HOME ELECTRONICS, FURNISHINGS, APPLIANCES (HMF)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- European countries, with some help from the
U.S., defeated a Japanese proposal to set uniform standards
for high-definition television, making it more likely that
the new technology will develop differently on three
continents.
   The decision to defer adopting an HDTV production
standard, made at an international telecommunications
conference in Duesseldorf, West Germany, was largely a
symbolic blow to the Japanese. Japan Broadcasting Corp. plans
to start high-definition TV broadcasts in Japan next summer,
after the launch of two video satellites. So far, the
Japanese are about one year behind schedule. European
television makers, grouped together within the Eureka EU 95
project, are pushing their own standards. So are Zenith
Electronics Corp. and others in the U.S.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   High-definition TV refers to a host of new technologies
aimed at producing video monitors with super-sharp images.
The technology has become an important trade issue because of
predictions that the new sets will come to dominate the
consumer electronics market and produce huge business for
makers of semiconductor chips. The first sets are expected to
go on sale in the U.S. in the mid-1990s.
   In 1986, Japan, backed by the U.S., proposed to set a
standard for the production of high-definition videotapes.
These standards would be important for producing such studio
equipment as cameras and professional video-tape recorders, a
relatively small market.
   The Japanese also apparently hoped that getting their
production standard approved would help win approval of a
separate standard for transmitting high-definition shows to
homes world-wide. Winning approval of that standard could
mean tens of millions of dollars in royalty payments and give
a leg-up to producers of the new television sets.
   European countries, which wanted to develop their own
standard to protect their electronics industries, defeated
the 1986 proposal. Since that time, the U.S. backed away from
the Japanese proposal, and the Europeans continued their
opposition.
   In the U.S., a production standard isn't likely to be
adopted until after 1993, when the Federal Communications
Commission is scheduled to chose a standard for HDTV
broadcasts. It now seems likely that the U.S., Europe and
Japan will use different production and transmission systems
for the new technology.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900525-0126
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900525-0126.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   GOP War Chest
   Surpasses by Far
   Democrats' Sum
   ---
   In 15 Months, Republicans
   Received $113 Million,
   Democrats $24 Million
   ----
   By Jill Abramson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The national Republican political committees
continue to hold a huge cash advantage over their Democratic
counterparts, according to a study by the Federal Election
Commission.
   In the 15 months ended in March, the three major
committees of the Republican Party raised a total of $113
million, compared with $24 million for the three Democratic
national committees. In overall spending, the Republicans
held a four-to-one lead over the Democrats.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   With the 1990 campaign season about to move into high
gear, the Republican committees had $19 million in cash
reserves at March 31; the Democrats had only $6 million on
hand. As impressive as are the GOP totals, however, the
Republican committees have yet to raise as much as they did
in 1984.
   Fundraising results for the Democratic National Committee
and the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee trailed
1986 and 1988 levels in the 15-month period covered by the
FEC study. But the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee,
which raised $10 million, surpassed its fund-raising totals
of 1986 and 1988.
   Still, Ron Brown, DNC chairman, said: "The DNC's
fund-raising program has made substantial progress over the
past year and is on track with the Democratic Party's
financial goals."
   At the same time the FEC released its study, the Democrats
made public a list of the party's top "soft money" donors,
who gave a total of $3.6 million to the party in 1989 and the
first quarter of 1990. Soft money consists of donations that
aren't spent directly on campaigns and thus aren't restricted
by federal election laws.
   Congress is considering a ban on "soft money" as part of
campaign-finance legislation. The DNC had resisted making
public its list of "soft money" contributors while the Senate
was considering the bill. Late last month, the Republican
Party released a list of wealthy donors who gave the party a
total of more than $7 million in "soft money" donations in
1989 and 1990.
   Among the top Democratic "soft money" contributors were a
number of labor unions, corporations and wealthy individuals.
They included: Archer-Daniels Midland Corp., $55,000;
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees,
$150,400; Frederick Field, a California investor, $103,400;
Monte Friedkin, a Florida millionaire, $100,000; Jerome
Kohlberg, a co-founder of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, $25,000;
National Education Association, $135,000; Maurice Tempelsman,
a New York diamond merchant, $25,000; United Steel Workers
union, $100,000; United Auto Workers union, $130,000. Mr.
Brown's Washington law firm, Patton, Boggs &amp; Blow gave
$10,500.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
