<HL>
   Ex-Thortec Officials
   Settle SEC Charges
   Of Inflating Results
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<CO>
   URS
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Securities and Exchange Commission
charged four former officials of Thortec International Inc.
with overstating the company's revenue and earnings in 1986
and 1987.
   Without admitting or denying the charges, each of the
officials consented to a permanent injunction barring them
from future violations of securities laws.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Thortec, which has since changed its name to URS Corp., is
a San Francisco-based architectural and engineering firm. The
four individuals are Richard Towle, former chief financial
officer; Arthur Whipple, former chief accounting officer;
Arthur Stromberg, former chairman and chief executive
officer; and Franklin Agardy, former chief operating officer.
   The SEC alleged that the individuals manipulated the
company's accounting records to record an extra $8.4 million
of revenue and earnings for the fiscal year ended Oct. 31,
1986, when the company reported revenue of $115.7 million and
net income of $8.7 million.
   The commission also alleged that results for the first two
quarters of fiscal 1987 were inflated by $5 million.
   "The individuals settled to put the matter behind them and
avoid protracted litigation," said Theodore Levine, a
Washington, D.C., attorney for Messrs. Stromberg, Agardy and
Whipple. "These were viewed as technical accounting issues,
and they wanted to resolve the matter. . . ."
   In Palo Alto, Calif., an attorney for Mr. Towle declined
comment.
   In San Francisco, a spokesman for URS Corp. noted that the
company isn't named in the complaint, and that the four
individuals who were are no longer with the company. He said
class-action suits against the company arising out of
charges, including some that concerned the SEC, were settled
last year "and are now behind us."
   He said "the company, over a year ago, voluntarily
restated certain of its financial statements, relating to all
of the matters covered by the SEC complaint." He added, "We
have a new management team, new auditors and very strong
financial controls in place now to ensure that a repetition
does not occur."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900525-0082
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900525-0082.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bill to Strengthen
   SEC Is Approved
   By a Senate Panel
   ----
   By Kevin G. Salwen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Senate Banking Committee unanimously
approved a bill that would give the Securities and Exchange
Commission substantially broader fining power and allow the
agency to shut down alleged securities-industry wrongdoers.
   The legislation also will give the SEC easier access to
grand-jury investigations in securities-law cases, a power
the SEC has sought since it found resources strapped by the
insider-trading cases of the mid- to late-1980s.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Senate version of the bill was amended prior to
committee approval to set stricter guidelines for the civil
fines, which would greatly expand the agency's enforcement
powers. The House hasn't moved far on its version of the
bill, which remains at the subcommittee level.
   Under the new system, a first tier sets a maximum of
$5,000 for each violation for individuals and $50,000 per
violation for brokerage firms and other entities for a range
of mostly inadvertent securities violations, such as late or
incorrect filings. The next tier sets maximums of $50,000 for
individuals and $250,000 for others if the violation involves
"fraud, deceipt, manipulation" or disregard for law. The
third level sets limits of $100,000 for individuals and
$500,000 for others if the second-tier criterion holds and
the violation "directly or indirectly resulted in substantial
losses."
   Currently, the SEC has the authority to impose fines for
insider-trading violations.
   The legislation approved by the panel allows the SEC to
order a brokerage firm or other entity regulated by the
agency to "cease and desist" from wrongdoing. That rule is
narrower than the earlier proposed legislation, which would
have allowed the SEC to take such unilateral action against a
corporation as well. Currently, the SEC must ask the courts
for a temporary injunction to stop such abuses.
   Under the bill's new authority, the SEC would still be
able to seek cease-and-desist authority over a corporate
violator if the company is provided with notice and an
opportunity for a hearing before the order is issued.
   The bill was tightened to relieve concerns that the SEC
would become too heavy-handed in its enforcement efforts. "We
have tried to address those concerns by clarifying the scope
of the bill in virtually every section," said Sen.
Christopher Dodd (D., Conn.), who heads the securities
subcommittee.
   The bill also would allow courts to bar officers or
directors from serving in those capacities if they are found
to have violated anti-fraud laws. Earlier versions of the
bill granted that power to the SEC, but corporate groups
contended that the authority was too broad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900525-0081
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900525-0081.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   California Democratic Race for Governor Pits
   Feinstein Style Against Van de Kamp Substance
   ----
   By James M. Perry
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<LP>
   HOLLYWOOD, Calif. -- The two-way contest for the
Democratic nomination for governor is widely seen as a battle
between substance and style, and so far style is winning.
   With the primary election only 11 days away, substance --
or at least the appearance of it -- is represented by
earnest, baby-faced John Van de Kamp, the state's
54-year-old, two-term attorney general. The stylish
candidate, almost everyone agrees, is the elegant,
fast-talking Dianne Feinstein, the 56-year-old former mayor
of San Francisco.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Van de Kamp is traveling up and down the state with
charts and graphs showing how he would balance the state's
budget. He says his opponent doesn't understand such things.
   Mrs. Feinstein is telling everyone how dedicated she is to
imposing the death penalty. She says Mr. Van de Kamp, who
personally opposes state executions, can't be trusted to use
the gas chamber frequently and effectively.
   If the polls are accurate, Mrs. Feinstein and the death
penalty are edging out Mr. Van de Kamp and his charts and
graphs. But the undecided vote is large in a race that hasn't
managed, until now, to keep California voters awake at night.
And, in these last days of campaigning, highlighted by a
debate here at a TV studio on Sunset Boulevard, Mr. Van de
Kamp for the first time has put Mrs. Feinstein on the
defensive.
   "It's going to be very close," says party chairman, and
former governor, Jerry Brown.
   Waiting in the wings is the forgotten man, the GOP
gubernatorial candidate, U.S. Sen. Pete Wilson, who hasn't
any serious opposition on the June 5 ballot.
   This is serious business, or should be. California faces
major problems in financing its public services, repairing
its highways, coping with crime and drugs, and educating a
school population that speaks so many languages it rivals the
Tower of Babel.
   There are significant national political implications,
too. California will pick up as many as seven new
congressional seats following this year's census and both
parties are eager to draw the new district lines to their
partisan advantage. Republicans, especially, need their own
governor to thwart the machinations of a Democratic
legislature.
   But somehow the gubernatorial campaign seems detached from
the real world facing Californians.
   If Mrs. Feinstein isn't celebrating the death penalty,
she's attacking Mr. Van de Kamp for refusing, as Los Angeles
district attorney, to prosecute the so-called Hillside
Strangler for murder nine years ago. It's a familiar story to
Californians. A judge took the case away from Mr. Van de Kamp
and gave it to the attorney general's office, which went on
to win a murder conviction. Mr. Van de Kamp has admitted,
again and again, that he made a mistake.
   Earlier this week, Mrs. Feinstein camped outside Mr. Van
de Kamp's office and insisted to the assembled reporters and
TV cameras it isn't enough "to grudgingly confess a mistake."
   At the same time, Mr. Van de Kamp digs into history to
charge that Mrs. Feinstein left a $180 million deficit to her
successor in her last city budget, for fiscal 1989. In fact,
Mrs. Feinstein's budget message projected a surplus, which
turned into a deficit soon after Art Agnos took office as
mayor. It isn't, in any event, a compelling story for
California voters.
   And if Mr. Van de Kamp isn't urging Mrs. Feinstein to own
up to the "d-word" (deficit), he's pointing to his charts and
graphs to explain a budget proposal that is more symbolic
than real.
   "It's a campaign gimmick," says Mrs. Feinstein. "Neither
one of us is involved in this budget, and that's the real
world." She misses the point, says Mr. Van de Kamp, in a
separate interview. "You propose and you learn. This is a
challenge to see which one of us has the competence to put a
budget together. She comes up short on knowing how to get
from A to B."
   The "g-word" -- gimmick -- explains a lot about this race.
   Each candidate is backed by professional political
consultants -- Robert Shrum for Mr. Van de Kamp, Bill Carrick
and Hank Morris for Mrs. Feinstein. They have set the tone.
   Mr. Shrum, in a typical Pygmalion-like production, took
his hard-working, nuts-and-bolts candidate, who concedes,
wistfully, that he prefers to operate "on the basis of
civility," and turned him into what one critic calls a
"slash-and-burn populist."
   Mr. Van de Kamp admits that his consultants have played a
role "in seeing what you are and what you've done." But he
says he's comfortable with that. He insists he really is a
populist, having taken on the entrenched interests for years.
"Look," he says, "historically I have always stood for the
little guy."
   His strategists, seeking ways to overcome the undoubted
reality that Mr. Van de Kamp lacks verve, came up with the
idea that their candidate would sponsor three high-impact
ballot initiatives: first, Big Green, an environmental
proposal that would cut back on the use of pesticides;
second, a measure to limit legislative terms to 12 years; and
third, a crime proposal that would speed up trials and
incarcerate drug offenders in abandoned housing on surplus
military land in the desert.
   At considerable cost, Mr. Van de Kamp's campaign rounded
up the signatures and the initiatives will all be on the
ballot in November.
   "Vote for my initiatives, vote for me," says Mr. Morris,
one of Mrs. Feinstein's consultants, explaining Mr. Van de
Kamp's strategy.
   It is an interesting strategy for defeating Sen. Wilson in
the fall, but it failed to take into account the challenge by
Mrs. Feinstein in the spring. "She's been a breath of fresh
air," says Assembly Speaker Willie Brown, one of her
supporters. "She brings a lot of drama and glamour to the
campaign."
   And she struck political gold with her first TV spot. It
showed viewers dramatic footage of the event that propelled
her into office -- the assassination in 1978 of Mayor George
Moscone. And it ended with the kicker that she is the only
Democrat running for governor who's for the death penalty.
   She builds on that image by talking about the time she
walked into a corner grocery store after a holdup in which
the grocer and his guard dog were both killed. "There was
brain matter all over the canned goods," she says. This sort
of wanton killing, she adds, "must be stopped, and I'm
absolutely dedicated to doing it."
   What's happened here is that a woman noted for the
compassion with which she pulled San Francisco together
following Mr. Moscone's murder has co-opted the crime issue
from a professional prosecutor with 30 years on the job.
   Mr. Van de Kamp has tried to respond with ads criticizing
Mrs. Feinstein's record as mayor. And, when that didn't seem
to work, he began running positive ads boasting of his
accomplishments -- a move that prompted a classic line from
Mrs. Feinstein's press secretary, Dee Dee Myers: "He's
resorted to the high road in desperation."
   Mr. Van de Kamp continues to confuse some voters by
boasting of the work he has done in putting killers on Death
Row, while saying that he is personally opposed to the death
penalty. And he says that he is personally opposed to
abortion, but would never do anything to interfere with a
woman's right to choose.
   "We can't afford to have a governor who is for what he's
against and against what he is for," says Mrs. Feinstein.
   And, yet, there is a chink in Mrs. Feinstein's armor, and
Mr. Van de Kamp is finally beginning to take advantage of it.
It is simply this: She doesn't always do her homework. The
result is that in debates and in interviews, she sometimes
blunders. These last few days, she's had to retract
statements twice. "I don't think I backed down," she says. "I
clarified my positions."
   The first time, she suggested she was willing in budget
talks to negotiate away cost-of-living increases for the
blind, the needy and the disabled. She "clarified" that
statement by saying that while she would put those allowances
on the table, she wouldn't give them away. In the second, she
suggested she might consider signing a bill to ban
sex-selection abortions if they became a problem in
California. Abortion-rights groups complained sex-selection
laws are "smoke screens" for anti-abortion groups. She
"clarified" that statement by saying she would never sign
such a bill.
   "It's fairly clear," says Mr. Van de Kamp, "she has no
ideas of her own."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
