<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Amtrak Spending Bill of $1.4 Billion
   For Next Two Years Is Vetoed by Bush
   ----
   By Laurie McGinley
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<IN>
RAILROADS (RAI)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
INTERSTATE COMMERCE COMMISSION (ICC)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- President Bush vetoed a bill authorizing
$1.4 billion in Amtrak spending for the next two fiscal
years, saying that a provision requiring increased government
review of freight-railroad takeovers represented a "step
backward for the entire rail industry."
   The disputed provision would have given the Interstate
Commerce Commission jurisdiction to review proposals by
non-railroad companies to acquire any of the nation's 16
largest freight railroads.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The ICC already has the authority to review the
acquisition of an entire railroad or a segment of it by
another railroad. It also has authority to review the
purchase of a piece of a railroad by a non-railroad company.
But it may not review the proposed takeover of an entire
railroad by a non-rail company -- a loophole that needed
closing, according to the proponents of the provision.
   President Bush disagreed, saying in his veto message to
Congress that the provision was "an unwarranted regulatory
roadblock to financial restructuring of the industry."
   Amtrak spokesman John Jacobsen said that, as a result of
the veto, "no trains are going to grind to a halt." But he
complained that it clouds Amtrak's financial future, making
it more difficult for the government-owned passenger railroad
to raise private capital.
   Prospects for a congressional override of the veto, which
would require two-thirds votes by both the House and the
Senate, are hard to gauge. The House passed the bill by an
overwhelming 322-93, but the Senate approved it on a voice
vote, so the depth of support isn't clear. Since President
Bush has taken office, Congress hasn't overridden any of his
10 previous vetoes.
   The Amtrak bill included authorization of $630 million for
fiscal 1989, which ended last Sept. 30, $656 million for
fiscal 1990, $684 million for fiscal 1991 and $712 million
for fiscal 1992. Congress has already appropriated funds for
the railroad for 1989 and 1990; the vetoed bill includes
authorizations for those years simply for bookkeeping
reasons.
   The administration, in its January budget proposal, hadn't
proposed any funding for Amtrak. But President Bush didn't
cite funding levels as a reason to veto the authorization
measure.
   Authorizing legislation defines which programs the
government may carry out and sets spending ceilings for them,
while appropriating legislation funds the programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900525-0061
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900525-0061.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   House Panel Votes
   To Freeze Target
   Prices of Grains
   ----
   By Bruce Ingersoll
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The House Agriculture Committee, bowing to
budget pressure, discarded a proposal to give grain farmers
an additional $6.5 billion in subsidies over the next five
years.
   The lawmakers, led by Committee Chairman Kika de la Garza
(D., Texas), continued to hold the line on farm spending,
voting unanimously to freeze so-called target prices for
wheat and feed grains at current levels from fiscal 1991
through 1995. The committee signaled a new era of frugalness
last week as it voted to freeze target prices for cotton and
rice and tentatively agreed to freeze grain target prices.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The committee also voted to establish a marketing-loan
program for soybeans, sunflowers and other oilseed crops, but
with the proviso that it would operate at no cost to the
government.
   Many farm-state lawmakers had wanted to tie target prices
for commodities to farm production costs, but that would have
added $6.5 billion above the baseline spending level.
Instead, the committee adopted a plan that would freeze
target prices for wheat at $4 a bushel, corn at $2.75, barley
at $2.36 and oats at $1.45.
   However, in years when the U.S. is expected to import more
oats than it exports, the agriculture secretary would be
authorized to allow farmers to harvest oats on land that
otherwise would be taken out of production to prevent
surpluses of other commodities. Lawmakers hope this provision
will provide an incentive to reverse the prolonged decline in
oat production.
   Under the farm program, the government dispenses
deficiency payments if market prices fall short of target
prices.
   After lengthy debate, the committee also adopted a plan to
give farmers a free hand to plant a variety of crops,
including experimental crops with industrial uses, on 25% of
the land they customarily devote to cotton, rice, wheat, feed
grains and oilseeds.
   But to mollify soybean processors and the American Soybean
Association, the lawmakers decided against allowing farmers
to plant such subsidized crops as cotton and corn on oilseed
acreage. The processors and the trade group fears a drop in
soybean production.
   But farmers who take advantage of this planting
flexibility provision wouldn't be eligible for subsidy
payments on that land.
   Last week, the lawmakers tentatively agreed to a 20%
flexibility provision.
   Committee staffers said freezing target prices would have
negligible impact on food prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
