WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST LATAM AFRIC
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The World Bank cleared $76.6 million in
loans to South Korea for technological research projects.
   The bank said $45 million will go to universities and
$31.6 million to several technology institutes, including the
Genetic Engineering Center, which supports South Korea's
biotechnology industry. Bank officials said the loans will
help strengthen South Korea's capacity for technological
innovation, while reducing its dependence on imported
technology.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Other loans approved by the World Bank and its affiliate,
the International Development Association, included these
recipients:
   -- Rwanda, $40 million from the IDA for roads and
transport-sector projects.
   -- Tanzania, $38.3 million from the IDA for primary and
secondary schools.
   -- Caribbean Development Bank, based in Barbados, $32
million from the World Bank and IDA, to help finance business
ventures and other projects in a group of Caribbean island
countries.
   -- Colombia, $24 million from the World Bank to expand
community child-care and nutrition projects for preschool
children.
   -- Central African Republic, $19 million from the IDA to
help preserve forests and wildlife areas.
   The World Bank loans carry a variable interest rate,
currently 7.75% a year; the IDA credits will be
interest-free, except for administrative fees.
