<HL>
   Japan's Nonlife Insurers
   Had Lower Net for Year
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN TKIOY J.YFM J.TMI J.SMF
</CO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Large growth in redemptions and claims as well as
financial instability drove down profits at Japan's nonlife
insurers in fiscal 1989.
   Interest-rate deregulation in Japan has led policy holders
in recent years to redeem annuities in favor of
higher-yielding bank deposits, resulting in lower investment
income and diminished assets as well as large payments. In
the fiscal year ended March 31, growth in investment income
was also depressed by instability in the Japanese financial
markets.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   To counter redemptions of annuities, the companies have
relied on growth in policies such as auto insurance for
business. An unusually high number of road accidents in the
year left all the companies exposed to large claims from
shareholders. Profits on insurance operations at the four
largest Japanese nonlife insurers fell sharply in the year.
   Those insurers are Tokio Marine &amp; Fire Insurance Co.,
Yasuda Fire &amp; Marine Insurance Co., Taisho Marine &amp; Fire
Insurance Co. and Sumitomo Marine &amp; Fire Insurance Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900525-0032
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900525-0032.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Par Pharmaceutical Inc.:
   President Granted Proxies
   Equal to 2 Million Shares
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<CO>
   PRX
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Par Pharmaceutical Inc. said its president was granted
proxies from four shareholders to vote about two million of
its shares in matters relating to board membership.
   The proxies, when combined with the shares owned by the
president, Kenneth I. Sawyer, give him beneficial ownership
of 17.8% of the Spring Valley, N.Y., generic drug company. In
a Securities and Exchange Commission filing, Mr. Sawyer said
he was granted the proxies to "help assure" certain
governmental agencies involved in investigating and reviewing
the generic drug industry and the company that the
shareholders support new management installed in September.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The proxies give Mr. Sawyer the right to vote the about
two million shares in matters relating to election or removal
of directors and filling board vacancies.
   Par has been the target of federal investigations for the
past two years. Earlier this year Par and its majority-owned
Quad Pharmaceuticals Inc. unit were fined a total of $400,000
for illegal gratuity payments made to an official of the Food
and Drug Administration. Par and Quad both have recalled
products amid concerns about adherence to regulatory
procedures.
</TEXT>
