<DOCNO>
WSJ900525-0003
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900525-0003.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Service America Says
   It Is in Default on Loan
   By Subsidiary of GE
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   X.SVA GE
</CO>
<LP>
   STAMFORD, Conn. -- Service America Corp. said it is in
default on a $195 million loan from General Electric Capital
Corp. and expects its losses to widen for the fiscal year
ended March 31.
   The food-service company blamed higher operating costs,
increased competition, and weakness in factory employment in
automobile plants and textile mills where it has significant
operations. The company also cited special charges for
severance and relocation expenses related to senior
management changes made in the last six months.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Service America said its senior creditor, GE Capital,
advised the company that under the loan accord, Service
America won't be permitted to make any payments on its
subordinated debt. The company said a $10.8 million interest
payment on its $127 million subordinated debt is due June 15.
   Service America said it and GE Capital, a unit of General
Electric Co., Fairfield, Conn., are discussing a
restructuring of its senior and subordinated debt. The
company plans to file a registration statement within 45 days
to offer a proposal to restructure its subordinated debt.
Meanwhile, it expects to be able to conduct normal operations
and to continue to draw against its $70 million
revolving-credit agreement with GE Capital to make payments
to suppliers, employees and other third parties except for
subordinated creditors.
   Service America said it expects to report that net losses
in the fiscal-fourth quarter and full year widened but that
revenue increased in both periods. In the fourth quarter of
last year, the company reported a net loss of $6.3 million on
revenue of $256.1 million. For the full 1989 fiscal year,
Service America had a net loss of $14.4 million on revenue of
$1.04 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900525-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900525-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Compaq Computer
   Directors Approve
   2-for-1 Stock Split
</HL>
<DATE>
05/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8
</SO>
<CO>
   CPQ
</CO>
<IN>
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<LP>
   HOUSTON -- Compaq Computer Corp., whose stock price has
sailed well above $100 a share, said its directors approved a
2-for-1 split of its common stock.
   The fast-growing computer concern said it believes the
move will make its stock more affordable for smaller
shareholders. Institutions hold an estimated 70% to 75% of
Compaq's shares.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In addition, companies often split their shares in the
belief that a lower price will help the stock price keep
rising. Compaq closed at $122, down 87.5 cents, in New York
Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Compaq said the stock split will be paid July 6 to holders
of record June 29.
   Daniel C. Benton, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co.,
said the move shows that Compaq, the nation's third-largest
maker of personal computers, is confident about its
prospects. But, he said, "I don't know that there is a whole
lot of empirical evidence that when you split a stock, the
stock does better.
   "I think it's mainly psychological for the companies," he
said.
   Since February, Compaq shares have soared to more than
$120 from around $80. Other technology stocks also have
climbed, fed by European demand for computers and
stronger-than-expected U.S. sales. Analysts attributed
Compaq's surge to renewed shareholder confidence after
Compaq's first-quarter earnings, reported last month,
surpassed most expectations. The company said net income rose
11% to $92.2 million, or $2.13 a share. Sales increased 28%
to $872.2 million.
   Compaq said in February that its share of the market for
high-end personal computers was dropping and warned of
stiffer competition in the personal-computer business. But it
said an unexpected 56% rise in overseas sales helped fuel its
first-quarter earnings increases.
</TEXT>
